Yes, we need to open up our economy with caution and safety measures in place to keep the cases low. The huge number of cases are confined to FWs. Singaporeans in general are prudent and understand the broad issues. Majority want to be safe too.  However, many businesses are suffering financial losses. Many families of middle and lower income group are also stressed out and worried about their livelihood. Entrepreneurs are asked qby govt to keep the jobs of their employees but are not given much assistance except the subsidies of 25% pay per employee capped at $4,600 ( only 3 industries get 75%). SMEs cannot sustain and keep paying the employees without income coming in. From where do the majority of entrepreneurs get the capital unless they have multi-millionaire parents? Temporary Bridging loans take a long time to approve. Multi-Nationals and govt agencies have deep pockets and at worst, MNCs can always retrench employees and pack up like in the 1980s. Then they come back again to re open when times are good. Local SMEs have no choice and very little help. Landlords are unwilling to give or help beyond what the govt's property tax rebates. Everyone has sympathy for frontliners and rightly so because it is a huge task that endangers their lives. However, to keep the economy and businesses going also means that Singaporeans will not have to go hungry, will not have to be Foreign Workers or Domestic helpers. Spore is one of the richest nations on earth but the core wealth is with the govt not the majority of the citizens.  SMEs need govt support too at this critical time to get through this very tough time. So Mr Wong, hope that this message gets to our govt.
